00:00:00.133 --> 00:00:03.303
So, I want to tell you a story
today about intelligence and

00:00:03.303 --> 00:00:07.074
intelligence collection. And
when you talk about

00:00:07.074 --> 00:00:10.844
intelligence, unless there's
been a well-known leak in the

00:00:10.844 --> 00:00:14.047
press or something, there ain't
a whole lot of examples to talk

00:00:14.047 --> 00:00:18.418
about. And we'll certainly talk
about those. But I was really

00:00:18.418 --> 00:00:21.488
wanting to do today is talk
about some actual projects. Most

00:00:21.488 --> 00:00:26.727
of the time my intelligence
clients, they don't want me to

00:00:26.727 --> 00:00:29.730
talk about what I'm doing for
them for obvious reasons.

00:00:29.730 --> 00:00:33.901
Sometimes I get lucky where I
was able to talk about it, but

00:00:33.901 --> 00:00:39.907
normally that's not the case. So
a couple of years ago, I decided

00:00:43.577 --> 00:00:48.815
that if I wanted to become my
own intelligence client, okay.

00:00:48.815 --> 00:00:51.385
So what I ended up doing is I
went into business with my

00:00:51.385 --> 00:00:57.558
girlfriend and we have an online
retail business. And it's doing

00:00:57.558 --> 00:01:03.563
pretty well. We're in our second
year. And it's growing. And I

00:01:03.563 --> 00:01:06.833
like to think the reason that
it's growing is not because we

00:01:06.833 --> 00:01:10.971
work hard, but we do work hard.
I like to think it's because we

00:01:10.971 --> 00:01:15.008
have got these little hacker
brains and we just have the

00:01:15.008 --> 00:01:21.014
sales channels that we use. And
I'll describe why that is

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:30.223
important in a bit here. The
other thing that's important for

00:01:30.223 --> 00:01:32.225
retail businesses is you want to
know exactly what kind of

00:01:32.225 --> 00:01:34.361
inventory to buy before you buy
it. I'll show you the

00:01:34.361 --> 00:01:38.765
intelligence that we use to do
that. And I'm also going to show

00:01:38.765 --> 00:01:45.005
you how we manipulate markets or
as I tell my mother, how we

00:01:45.005 --> 00:01:50.277
protect our investments. All
right. So when people hear the

00:01:50.277 --> 00:01:54.147
word intelligence, usually they
think immediately, military

00:01:54.147 --> 00:01:57.117
intelligence, right? Well, this,
there's not a whole of that that

00:01:57.117 --> 00:02:00.354
applies to what we do. The other
side of it is either business

00:02:00.354 --> 00:02:02.489
intelligence or competitive
intelligence. And those two are

00:02:02.489 --> 00:02:05.759
really pretty different, but I
think it's important that we

00:02:05.759 --> 00:02:10.263
describe the differences between
the two. Business intelligence

00:02:10.263 --> 00:02:15.902
is what's happening within your
business. You use internal data

00:02:15.902 --> 00:02:22.075
and you focus on knowing your
operations and you focus on

00:02:22.075 --> 00:02:26.546
knowing your resources. And what
you really are trying to do is

00:02:26.546 --> 00:02:31.118
make the whole operation just
more effective and more

00:02:31.118 --> 00:02:37.124
efficient and everything. And
that's all very useful. But it's

00:02:51.838 --> 00:02:54.841
also very different than
competitive intelligence.

00:02:54.841 --> 00:02:56.910
Because with competitive
intelligence, you're trying to

00:02:56.910 --> 00:03:00.580
find what's happening outside
your organization. It doesn't

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:06.186
matter if you're a business or a
political organization or if you

00:03:06.186 --> 00:03:10.657
are a investigative journalist
trying to collect information.

00:03:10.657 --> 00:03:14.027
This is all more competitive
intelligence. You're using

00:03:14.027 --> 00:03:18.799
external data, and your focus is
on knowing your competitors and

00:03:18.799 --> 00:03:22.936
knowing your markets. So this is
the area where we're going to

00:03:22.936 --> 00:03:25.806
live today. We're going to live
in the competitive intelligence

00:03:25.806 --> 00:03:30.777
area. So a lot of people, they
think competitive intelligence,

00:03:30.777 --> 00:03:37.250
that's kind of murky. But it's
important to know that

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:40.720
competitive intelligence is
taught in every top business

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:45.559
school. In fact if you are
running a business, it's your

00:03:45.559 --> 00:03:49.262
responsibility to do this kind
of stuff. It's also important to

00:03:49.262 --> 00:03:51.965
know that there is actually a
professional association of

00:03:51.965 --> 00:03:55.202
people who do competitive
intelligence, with newsletters

00:03:55.202 --> 00:04:01.441
and conferences and that whole
thing. So I want to talk about

00:04:01.441 --> 00:04:05.212
the title a little bit, applied
intelligence. So when I'm

00:04:05.212 --> 00:04:08.715
talking about applied
intelligence, I'm talking about

00:04:08.715 --> 00:04:12.752
intelligence that's actionable.
Something that's going to change

00:04:12.752 --> 00:04:17.224
the way you're doing things. The
problem is that most of the

00:04:17.224 --> 00:04:20.393
intelligence that's collected
for the organizations that do

00:04:20.393 --> 00:04:25.766
collect it, it's not actionable.
It won't actually change what

00:04:25.766 --> 00:04:31.772
they're doing. And the other
problem is most organizations

00:04:31.772 --> 00:04:35.342
tend to overcollect intelligence
when they do collect it. So when

00:04:35.342 --> 00:04:38.445
you do that, it comes at a
higher cost, and you've got more

00:04:38.445 --> 00:04:42.616
exposure. The other thing is
that a lot of the intelligence

00:04:42.616 --> 00:04:45.552
that's collected is done because
people just feel obligated to

00:04:45.552 --> 00:04:51.625
collect. Not with any real
reason. So, for example, I don't

00:04:51.625 --> 00:04:53.927
know how many of you saw this.
This is something I had up, I

00:04:53.927 --> 00:04:58.431
was tweeting about it. I came up
with a little scraper that every

00:04:58.431 --> 00:05:01.701
hour would go after the Def Con
site and it would make it a

00:05:01.701 --> 00:05:07.574
printable mobile version of the
Def Con speaker schedule and

00:05:07.574 --> 00:05:10.710
it's still up there if you're
looking for it. And if you go

00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:14.681
through my Twitter account you
can find it. So I'm doing this

00:05:14.681 --> 00:05:17.751
and it's cool and it's useful
and I know a lot of people were

00:05:17.751 --> 00:05:20.854
using it because I was
collecting analytics on this

00:05:20.854 --> 00:05:25.192
stuff, right? So I got the
access time, IP addresses, I

00:05:25.192 --> 00:05:27.828
wrote a cookie so I could tell
if people were looking at it

00:05:27.828 --> 00:05:32.766
more than once. But this is more
analytics. It's not really

00:05:32.766 --> 00:05:36.703
intelligence. And the reason I
don't consider this to be good

00:05:36.703 --> 00:05:41.241
intelligence is because there's
absolutely nothing in these logs

00:05:41.241 --> 00:05:44.911
that would have changed anything
that I was doing. In fact, the

00:05:44.911 --> 00:05:48.148
only thing that I found that was
really interesting is probably

00:05:48.148 --> 00:05:52.352
about 90% of the traffic was
bots. It wasn't even human

00:05:52.352 --> 00:05:56.089
activity. But again that's not
going to really affect anything

00:05:56.089 --> 00:05:59.993
that I was doing. Now, if I
wanted to make this implied

00:05:59.993 --> 00:06:03.663
intelligence, what I could have
done is instead of just having a

00:06:03.663 --> 00:06:07.734
static table with all the
schedule on it, I could have

00:06:07.734 --> 00:06:11.771
given people the option to click
on the talks they wanted to go

00:06:11.771 --> 00:06:17.444
to, and I could have generated a
nice little schedule for people

00:06:17.444 --> 00:06:21.681
to take along. Oh, 4:00 I need
to be on this track. That would

00:06:21.681 --> 00:06:25.886
have been handy. And it also
potentially would have created

00:06:25.886 --> 00:06:29.489
some actionable intelligence.
Because if I had this

00:06:29.489 --> 00:06:33.693
information, and if I had it in
aggregate, I could make some

00:06:33.693 --> 00:06:37.697
projections as to which talks
are going to be really popular,

00:06:37.697 --> 00:06:41.434
which ones are we going to run
out of seating, and it could

00:06:41.434 --> 00:06:44.904
have been useful for people
doing speaker ops. I didn't do

00:06:44.904 --> 00:06:49.175
any of this kind of stuff, but I
see the potential use that could

00:06:49.175 --> 00:06:53.813
have changed the way things were
done. Okay. The second part of

00:06:53.813 --> 00:06:57.751
the title, information that's
not there, or isn't there, that

00:06:57.751 --> 00:07:02.555
is a direct reference to
metadata. Now, for most of us,

00:07:02.555 --> 00:07:06.626
we had no idea what metadata was
until the Edward Snowden

00:07:06.626 --> 00:07:10.297
disclosures came across, and
suddenly we heard the word

00:07:10.297 --> 00:07:14.434
surveillance, we all know what
that is. And we knew that things

00:07:14.434 --> 00:07:19.539
that we were doing online, on
our phones, even at the library,

00:07:19.539 --> 00:07:23.643
were now subject to surveillance
and there was something called

00:07:23.643 --> 00:07:28.181
metadata that was involved in
this. And people in the United

00:07:28.181 --> 00:07:33.486
States, we were pretty much
confused. But fortunately we

00:07:33.486 --> 00:07:39.726
have public officials that can
help us in this area. So Diane

00:07:39.726 --> 00:07:44.064
Fine Stein comes up and says
this was a hastily called

00:07:44.064 --> 00:07:50.403
meeting, and she goes as you
know, this is just metadata.

00:07:50.403 --> 00:07:56.209
There's no content involved.
Okay. So as a citizen of the

00:07:56.209 --> 00:07:59.679
United States, this made me feel
pretty damn good, right? It's

00:07:59.679 --> 00:08:04.184
just, okay. So you know I went
to the library but you don't

00:08:04.184 --> 00:08:06.853
know what I looked at? Okay.
That's pretty good. So then our

00:08:06.853 --> 00:08:13.059
own president got involved. So
nobody is listening to your

00:08:13.059 --> 00:08:16.229
phone calls. That's not what
this program is about. They're

00:08:16.229 --> 00:08:19.232
just looking at names or they're
not looking at names and they're

00:08:19.232 --> 00:08:23.069
not looking at content. But
sifting through the so-called

00:08:23.069 --> 00:08:29.376
metadata. They're sifting
through the data. I'm pretty

00:08:29.376 --> 00:08:33.346
familiar with data. I'm not
familiar with a sift command.

00:08:33.346 --> 00:08:39.552
(Laughter.) So this was good.
This was very good. (Applause.)

00:08:39.552 --> 00:08:45.558
Now I know more about metadata.
You can sift it. So I'm starting

00:08:50.263 --> 00:08:53.767
to feel pretty good about
metadata. But I really got

00:08:53.767 --> 00:08:57.103
confused then when Michael
Hayden, who is the former NSA

00:08:57.103 --> 00:09:00.807
boss chimed in, he said oh, we
kill people based on metadata.

00:09:00.807 --> 00:09:06.813
(Laughter.) So okay, I need to
know a little more now. I need

00:09:12.552 --> 00:09:17.157
to know just a little more.
Okay. So metadata. Metadata is

00:09:17.157 --> 00:09:21.561
so important, and it's largely
misunderstood. And we probably

00:09:21.561 --> 00:09:25.765
all know that metadata is data
that describes other data,

00:09:25.765 --> 00:09:30.804
right? But more importantly than
that, it's data that provides

00:09:30.804 --> 00:09:37.710
context for information. And
usually the very best metadata

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:43.116
doesn't even really exist. It
needs to be created. And that's

00:09:43.116 --> 00:09:49.389
where the fun is. That's where
the data hacking happens. So if

00:09:49.389 --> 00:09:55.328
you study metadata academically
in college, they've got this

00:09:55.328 --> 00:10:00.433
whole plethora of categories for
metadata, I like to keep it

00:10:00.433 --> 00:10:04.404
simple and say there's two kinds
basically. There's parametric

00:10:04.404 --> 00:10:08.341
data, that's data that has to be
collected or created and then

00:10:08.341 --> 00:10:12.278
there's imbedded data. And this
is probably where most people

00:10:12.278 --> 00:10:16.316
got familiar with metadata
initially, like in the '90s. And

00:10:16.316 --> 00:10:20.220
that's generally user created.
It tends to be stuff like the

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:23.690
imbedded headers on a digital
photograph that describes the

00:10:23.690 --> 00:10:29.062
camera that was used, when the
picture was taken, the F-stops,

00:10:29.062 --> 00:10:34.634
geo codes. This has become a
whole branch of law now because

00:10:34.634 --> 00:10:39.072
it's all admissible in courts.
I've got a couple of examples of

00:10:39.072 --> 00:10:43.576
these of data that's leaked this
way. This is one I used last

00:10:43.576 --> 00:10:45.912
year if you were at my talk and
I'm using it again because I

00:10:45.912 --> 00:10:51.417
just love it. This is a selfie
of a Russian soldier that was

00:10:51.417 --> 00:10:54.988
uploaded to Instagram. And
unfortunately, before he

00:10:54.988 --> 00:10:58.825
uploaded it, he didn't remove
the geo codes. So it revealed

00:10:58.825 --> 00:11:01.494
the fact that while his
government said they had no

00:11:01.494 --> 00:11:07.267
troops in Ukraine, he was in
Ukraine. Another example,

00:11:07.267 --> 00:11:10.403
another war-related example,
this is kind of a famous one.

00:11:10.403 --> 00:11:16.709
This is the Tony Blair memo.
This is the memo that was the

00:11:16.709 --> 00:11:21.781
justification for the invasion
of Iraq in what, 2002 or 2003,

00:11:21.781 --> 00:11:26.619
something like that. Right after
9/11. And it was actually used

00:11:26.619 --> 00:11:30.757
by Colin Powell when he went to
the United Nations to make his

00:11:30.757 --> 00:11:34.394
justification. And the
assumption was that this was

00:11:34.394 --> 00:11:38.198
done by area specialists and it
was all original work,

00:11:38.198 --> 00:11:43.770
well-researched. We find out it
was actually plagiarized. And

00:11:43.770 --> 00:11:47.674
not just plagiarized, but it was
plagiarized by a graduate

00:11:47.674 --> 00:11:51.711
student someplace in the UK. Oh,
that was the original document

00:11:51.711 --> 00:11:55.615
was a graduate student's paper.
And they know it was plagiarized

00:11:55.615 --> 00:11:58.518
because not only was the content
the same, but so were the

00:11:58.518 --> 00:12:02.455
grammatical errors. So where
this gets interesting though is

00:12:02.455 --> 00:12:07.060
in the metadata, Microsoft
Office files are full of

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:14.067
metadata. If you look at the
metadata here, we can see here

00:12:14.067 --> 00:12:18.037
that the people who did the
plagiarizing, we can figure out

00:12:18.037 --> 00:12:21.107
who they were and we can see
that they were not area

00:12:21.107 --> 00:12:23.876
specialists but they were
actually political advisers to

00:12:23.876 --> 00:12:29.082
Tony Blair so it's kind of a
nasty thing. This kind of stuff

00:12:29.082 --> 00:12:35.855
happens a lot though. The CEO of
Google a couple of years ago, he

00:12:35.855 --> 00:12:39.626
wanted to just put a PowerPoint
presentation online that was

00:12:39.626 --> 00:12:42.362
just kind of a general status
report for how things were

00:12:42.362 --> 00:12:48.167
happening. What he neglected to
do though is when he made that

00:12:48.167 --> 00:12:50.903
report, he actually made a copy
of a very confidential

00:12:50.903 --> 00:12:55.375
PowerPoint presentation that was
for internal use only and he did

00:12:55.375 --> 00:12:59.412
a lot of editing of the slides.
What he neglected to do was edit

00:12:59.412 --> 00:13:04.250
the speaker notes and he
released the specifics of a

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:08.655
project called Google drive and
it was well before it was

00:13:08.655 --> 00:13:14.494
officially announced. So watch
what you put in your speaker

00:13:14.494 --> 00:13:19.032
notes because it's out there.
Okay. So let's talk -- that was

00:13:19.032 --> 00:13:22.468
imbedded metadata. Let's look a
little about parametric metadata

00:13:22.468 --> 00:13:28.541
and see how that's used. So
according to the NSA, this is

00:13:28.541 --> 00:13:32.211
their own admission, this is
what they collect. They collect

00:13:32.211 --> 00:13:36.516
phone numbers of parties making
phone calls; they collect the

00:13:36.516 --> 00:13:41.421
time a call was placed; they
collect the duration of a phone

00:13:41.421 --> 00:13:47.160
call; and also who initiated the
call. Okay? That's kind of

00:13:47.160 --> 00:13:51.431
invasive, right? But you know,
it's actually -- they're not

00:13:51.431 --> 00:13:55.468
doing anything that any Android
app isn't making available to

00:13:55.468 --> 00:13:59.138
the developer, right? Stuff is
in there. It's in all your

00:13:59.138 --> 00:14:04.343
phones if you have an Android.
But with this metadata, you can

00:14:04.343 --> 00:14:07.513
get a lot of really interesting
stuff. What they're really after

00:14:07.513 --> 00:14:11.684
is the relationships between
callers. Because the metadata

00:14:11.684 --> 00:14:14.754
creates the context within the
phone calls, how they were

00:14:14.754 --> 00:14:18.324
placed, and within that you can
figure out the relationships

00:14:18.324 --> 00:14:21.694
with the callers. And these
relationships can then be

00:14:21.694 --> 00:14:25.098
profiled. And once you've
profiled them you can pick up

00:14:25.098 --> 00:14:28.735
the anomalies and outliers. And
at that point it becomes

00:14:28.735 --> 00:14:32.905
possible to differentiate
between a phone call being made

00:14:32.905 --> 00:14:36.375
by a parent at work to their
child, making sure they got home

00:14:36.375 --> 00:14:39.212
from school okay. That phone
call is going to look very

00:14:39.212 --> 00:14:42.882
different than some criminal
operative calling in for

00:14:42.882 --> 00:14:46.119
instructions. It's going to look
very different. And they're also

00:14:46.119 --> 00:14:48.621
able to identify things like
burner phones because those are

00:14:48.621 --> 00:14:50.623
things like big outliers since
those are the things that stick

00:14:50.623 --> 00:14:56.796
up. The other thing is you can
look at the patterns that people

00:14:56.796 --> 00:14:59.899
are calling and the
relationships and you can tie

00:14:59.899 --> 00:15:03.169
them to other events and if
other events affect the way

00:15:03.169 --> 00:15:06.372
people relate, there may be a
connection between that and

00:15:06.372 --> 00:15:09.142
those events. So these are the
kinds of things that the NSA

00:15:09.142 --> 00:15:14.180
looks for. These are the real
red flags. And they'll go three

00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:18.951
hops. So what that means is if
you have a phone call

00:15:18.951 --> 00:15:22.588
unknowingly with somebody who
has had a phone call with

00:15:22.588 --> 00:15:26.225
somebody who is a person of
interest, now suddenly you're

00:15:26.225 --> 00:15:29.395
kind of a person of interest
too. So that's how that all

00:15:29.395 --> 00:15:35.701
works. So you could look at this
and say yeah, it makes sense

00:15:35.701 --> 00:15:39.906
that they would look at metadata
because it's the easy way out.

00:15:39.906 --> 00:15:42.809
Otherwise they would have to
look at all these conversations

00:15:42.809 --> 00:15:45.745
and they would probably have to
do some kind of speech-to-text

00:15:45.745 --> 00:15:49.649
conversion and deal with
languages and they would have to

00:15:49.649 --> 00:15:54.987
deal with dialects and all that
kind of stuff. But it's just

00:15:54.987 --> 00:15:58.191
better data. Just flat out
better data. It's already

00:15:58.191 --> 00:16:03.296
digital. It can be processed.
But it needs to be created.

00:16:03.296 --> 00:16:06.532
That's the important thing about
metadata. All these

00:16:06.532 --> 00:16:10.169
relationships and stuff need to
be figured out. It's kind of

00:16:10.169 --> 00:16:14.340
like how long do you need to
play the game of Clue before you

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:18.878
know it's Mrs. Peacock killing
colonel mustard in the library

00:16:18.878 --> 00:16:22.915
with a candle stick. If you're
good at it you'll figure it out

00:16:22.915 --> 00:16:28.921
before other people playing the
game. How do we do metadata? How

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:40.600
do we process things? Well, I'm
not the NSA. I don't have

00:16:40.600 --> 00:16:45.838
unlimited resources and stuff.
So the area where I live is

00:16:45.838 --> 00:16:50.843
called operational security or
op sec. That is a military term.

00:16:50.843 --> 00:16:55.948
What that refers to is looking
at your day-to-day operations to

00:16:55.948 --> 00:16:59.485
see what kind of intelligence
you're leaking. And if you have

00:16:59.485 --> 00:17:04.323
an adversary looking at your
day-to-day operations, what kind

00:17:04.323 --> 00:17:08.227
of actionable intelligence can
they collect? Well, I do this

00:17:08.227 --> 00:17:13.199
online. The Internet is my
theater. So I look at things

00:17:13.199 --> 00:17:17.336
like employment postings. Last
year I gave examples about how

00:17:17.336 --> 00:17:21.240
companies leak strategic plans
through their employment

00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:23.976
postings, and I think you can
kind of figure out how that

00:17:23.976 --> 00:17:28.915
could probably happen, right? If
you think individuals leak

